@article{Chakrapani2017,
abstract = {Next generation cellular networks (5G) have to deal with deployment of
massive machine-type-communication (MTC) devices as the internet of
things (IoT) becomes pervasive. To cater to such demand, 3GPP has
finalized specifications for enhanced machine type communication (eMTC)
and narrowband IoT (NBIoT) as part of LTE Release 13(1). To avoid
resource congestion to legacy users, eMTC communication can be limited
to predefined eMTC narrowband(s) with receiver bandwidth of 1.08MHz,
whereas in NB-IoT all communications are limited to a single resource
block(2). Both eMTC and NB-IoT are designed to cater for bandwidth
limited low complexity/coverage enhancement (BL/CE) devices, with MTC
messages repeated across several BL/CE subframes lasting up to several
seconds, to accomodate for large maximum coupling losses (MCL). To avoid
MTC users from hogging, collide with legacy resources during lengthy
repetitions, 3GPP defines BL/CE subframes and has made provisions for
valid and invalid BL/CE subframes to be configured. With large number of
MTC devices sharing limited resources and message repetitions lasting
several SFs, the LTE medium access control (MAC) scheduler processing
burden will be significantly increased. This is because the scheduler
operates on a subframe (SF) basis and has to find the MTC users who can
be scheduled either in the current SF, or at a future SF after ongoing
repetitions finish, or within a gap between previously scheduled
repetitions. Another complexity is that the control messages(e.g.,
MPDCCH) can only be scheduled at certain start intervals and within
predefined boundaries. In this paper we address these problems with a
low complexity constant time scheduling scheme for MTC users(3) when
invalid BL/CE SFs are configured. The proposed algorithms are generic
and applicable to both eNB and UE implementation. With detailed system
level simulations we demonstrate the usefulness of the proposed scheme
when large number of MTC users are active in the system.},
